default&#xa0;defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
defaultGlobal is a media and entertainment company comprising
default Global Radio, Global TV, Global Publishing (music publishing) and Global Talent (artist management). Our brands include Heart, Capital, Classic FM, Smooth, LBC, Gold, XFM and Capital X
defaultTRA 
defaultbroadcasting from 21 broadcast centres across the country to over 2
default2 million listeners on every week.
defaultAside from our award winning talk station LBC, we are known for our music stations. We combine our passion for great music with impartial national and local news, weather, traffic and travel and local information. We comp
defaultete for listeners with the BBC’s national stations, Radio1, Radio2 and Radio3, other commercial stations and increasingly with online music and entertainment services.
default&#xa0;
defaultOur submission focuses on the areas where the BBC has the most significant impact on th
defaulte services we provide; national radio, local radio, digital innovation and patronage of classical music. We address the questions posed by the committee where they cover these areas. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Commercial Radio Industry default&#xa0;
defaultThe commercial radio sector generated r
defaultevenue of £472m in 2012, equivalent to about 3% of the UK advertising market. Industry revenue grew by nearly 4% in 2012, after many years of structural decline.
default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough it is a small part of the UK media industry commercial radio is a much-loved medium 
defaultand goes from strength to strength. It has 35 million listeners, reaching 66% of the population. Listeners spend an average 12.8 hours listening to commercial radio per week.
defaultThe revolution in digital technology and services in the past decade has transfor
defaultmed how commercial radio attracts listeners and advertising income. Our competitive pressures have been irreversibly altered by the arrival of the smartphone and internet; advertisers increasingly invest in online marketing and listeners, especially younge
defaultr people, are inundated with free online music services and ways to personalise their listening. 
defaultThe widening access to technology has led to the launch of many internet music-streaming services, dramatically changing the way consumers can listen to music
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultEqually important for the radio industry was the launch of the TuneIn in 2002. TuneIn Radio is available through a range of apps for iphones, ipads, Android, BlackBerry, Samsung, Windows Phone and has transformed smartphones into a gateway to radio ac
defaultross the world. TuneIn offers access to over 100,000 live 
defaultworldwide 
defaultradio stations. It has 40 million active listeners a month.
default&#xa0;
defaultNew digital innovation is transforming the way people consume music and entertainment. Consumers have never had such a varied c
defaulthoice of radio stations and music nor has it ever been so readily available.  The future of the BBC has to be evaluated with this in mind; the BBC is no longer necessary to increase choice for consumes as it was decades ago. 
default&#xa0;defaultThe futuredefault of the BBC in a digital agedefault&#xa0;
defaultGlobal believes that the BBC makes a valuable contribution to British radio and offers listeners many unique services that are not available on commercial radio. We want to see a successful and efficient BBC in the media secto
defaultr and support the principle of funding by the licence fee. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOur concerns and recommendations regarding the future of the BBC stem from our belief that far too often the BBC strays into areas where the private sector is already operating and serving consum
defaulters. This is unwelcome because it places the BBC in competition with the private sector and uses public funding to duplicate services that are already available free at the point of use.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC does not appear to have a coherent strategy to deliver pub
defaultlic service through its radio stations, particularly Radio1 and Radio2. In the absence of such a strategy the stations are run like commercial stations, pursuing mass-market appeal and ever-higher listener ratings. There is evidence to suggest that current
default leading BBC stations seek to maximise listener numbers and hours spent listening. These metrics are not appropriate for a public service broadcaster. The BBC should instead focus on high quality, distinctive content and underserved audiences, not on conte
defaultnt with wide appeal for mainstream audiences that is, or would be absent the BBC’s market intervention, provided by commercial operators at no cost to the licence-fee payer. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC is neglecting its public service remit. The BBC’s most popular radio sta
defaulttions broadcast negligible amounts of public service content, mostly in off-peak hours. Peak listening hours are reserved for popular music programmes which compete directly with commercial services. A lack of public service content represents poor value f
defaultor money for licence fee payers; public subsidy should be used exclusively to deliver services above and beyond those provided by the market. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA lack of effective checks and balances in BBC governance, which would compel stations to articulate and implement a strategy embedded in public service, has led to the failure of BBC radio stations to deliver sufficient public service content. Appropriate
default governance measures must be put in place post 2016 so that Government, licence fee payers and the private sector can have confidence that the BBC will not continue to use public funds to run populist, mainstream services already provided by the market. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOur submission focuses on four recommendations* for the future of the BBC: 
default&#xa0;
default▪
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe purpose of public service broadcasting should be more tightly defined beyond 2016. BBC content should be distinctive, not provided by the market, focus on audiences otherwise 
defaultunderserved and it should not encroach on commercial provision. Each BBC service should be accountable for meeting a clearly-defined public service remit. 
default&#xa0;
default▪
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBBC investment in technology and digital services must be more effectively evaluated before and dur
defaulting development. Once complete, projects should be evaluated for their impact on the market on an ongoing basis and consideration given to whether they are sold or made available to the private sector. There should be a role for peer review involving figur
defaultes from the private sector.   
default&#xa0;
default▪
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA ten-year royal charter and agreement is too long in a rapidly changing media market. There should be scope for intermediate reviews and evaluation while ensuring stability at the BBC. 
default&#xa0;
default▪
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe BBC should be more transparent a
defaultbout accounting and spending. The NAO should be given full access to the BBC accounts.
default&#xa0;
default* Classic FM will be making a separate submission to the Committee recommending that parts of the licence fee used to support the arts should be open to competition to 
defaultensure that the widest possible audience can access content. 
default&#xa0;defaultThe purpose of public service broadcastingdefault&#xa0;
defaultCommittee questions 
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow well has the BBC performed in
default the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes?
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAre the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat scope, scale and remit should the BBC have?
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultShould the BBC
default’
defaults output and services be provide
defaultd to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences?
default&#xa0;
defaultThe purpose of public service broadcasting should be to create distinctive content of public value and to serve audiences otherwise underserved. Although the six public purposes of the BBC have m
defaulterit, they are vague, too broad and do not give the corporation a clear mission or set of objectives. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThese purposes need to be superseded by a new set of more specific duties. These should take precedence over public purposes.  
default&#xa0;
defaultWe therefore believe th
defaultat the BBC’s duties in the Charter should include:  
default1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA duty to create content and undertake activities of public value with wider benefits for society 
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA duty to have regard to the market impact of its activities 
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA duty to evaluate the market impact of 
defaultnew products and projects before and after launch
default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA duty to serve audiences and minorities that are underserved by other media 
default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA duty where possible to create distinct and original content from other media, where possible
default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA duty to provide value for money
default for the license fee payer by 
defaultavoiding duplication of content already provided by the market 
default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA duty to have its accounts audited by the National Audit Office
default&#xa0;
defaultThis new framework, when applied to radio will result in more efficient BBC radio stations, deli
defaultvering unique public service content and distinctive content to underserved audiences. It will also mean that when the BBC invests in new technology, it is technology that would not otherwise come to market or that brings BBC content to audiences when it w
defaultould not otherwise be available. 
default&#xa0;defaultBBC radio in a digital age default&#xa0;
defaultAs the owners of Capital and Heart, two of the UKs largest commercial radio networks, playing contemporary and chart music, we are well placed to comment on the appeal and programming of Radio1 and Radio2. It is these stations that are the furthest from de
defaultlivering on their remit and most closely emulate commercial stations. 
default&#xa0;
defaultRadio1 and Radio2 date back to an era of limited consumer choice, before the launch of commercial radio, and long before music became so widely available through online and mobile serv
defaultices such as Youtube, Spotify and others. Radio1 and Radio2 can no longer justifiably claim to be providing a unique service, or one which 
defaultwould not be provided by the commercial sector. 
default  
defaultAs already described, the market now gives consumers access to a wi
defaultde choice of music, free at the point of use. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn future, the role of BBC radio stations should be dictated by the public duties we have outlined above. Rather than playing popular music for a mass audience they should primarily broadcast distinctive, ori
defaultginal content aimed at underserved audiences.  To do this effectively, 
default the culture at 
defaultBBC radio station
defaults must be radically changed and
default remits must be overhauled: they need to be much more specific and rooted in the duties we have set out. Managers must be
default held accountable for running services in line with remits. 
default 
defaultAt present, station managers appear to pay little attention to station remits and are not held accountable if they are not implemented.  
default&#xa0;defaultCASE STUDY: RADIO 1default&#xa0;
defaultThe remit of Radio1, set by t
defaulthe BBC Trust, is “to entertain and engage a broad range of young listeners with a distinctive mix of contemporary music and speech. It should reflect the lives and interests of 15–29 year olds but also embrace others who share similar tastes.
default&#xa0;
default“It should 
defaultoffer a range of new music, support emerging artists – especially those from the UK – and provide a platform for live music. News, documentaries and advice campaigns should cover areas of relevance to young adults.”
default&#xa0;
defaultIf Radio1 were a new publicly funder se
defaultrvice it would not be approved for launch because the remit is vague and does not place an emphasis on public service content or serving an audience not effectively reached by commercial radio, teenagers for example. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs it stands, this remit has allowed 
defaultthe BBC to build the Radio1 schedule around high profile presenters and popular music shows to chase ratings. New music shows, documentaries or high value informative speech are rare and invariably buried in off-peak hours. 
