default&#xa0;defaultBBC investment in technology and digital services default&#xa0;
defaultCommittee questions 
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?
default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC has a mixed record on technology. BBC investment has had a positive impact on new technology and platforms but it has wanted money products that are already available.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe evolution of the internet services market had matured in the past decade 
defaultand the need for a public funded intervention from the BBC has been reduced. For example, iplayer was the BBC’s largest intervention in this area and at the time it was the first of its kind. Now there are many versions of catch-up television and the BBC n
defaulto longer needs to keep financing such innovation. 
default&#xa0;
defaultNow the market is more developed the BBC needs a new approach to its investment. Its spending should be should be driven by content, for example, only investing in technology if it facilitates access to BBC content that would not otherwise be available. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAny activity should have a clearly articulated benefit to the license fee payer. Where possible, the BBC's activity should take place at the earlier stages of technological development where the BBC involvement could help seed a market for further innovati
defaulton by third parties.
default&#xa0;
defaultAny activity should seek to minimise negative market impact and the crowding out of commercial operators. Activity should not interfere with a pre-existing commercial market. BBC innovation must not crowd out start-ups who cannot hope
default to compete with the levels of funding available to the BBC. 
default&#xa0;defaultCase studies defaultPlaylister is a service that means whenever the BBC plays a song consumers can tag it and it will appear in one of three commercial music streaming services of which they are us
defaulters (Deezer, Spotify and YouTube are the chosen private partners). 
default&#xa0;
defaultPlaylister fails on all three principles: it is not an innovation around BBC content (the BBC does not create or own the music that the service links to); its benefit is not clearly artic
defaultulated to the license fee payer and the service is already sufficiently provided by the market (e.g Last.fm, Shazam, SoundHound, Facebook to name only a few); and, the small list of partners chosen to link from the service discriminates against other playe
defaultrs in the market place. The service is nothing more than a marketing channel for the three commercial services with whom the BBC has chosen to partner.
defaultiPlayer Radio app has been released into a market already well supplied with radio station aggregator 
defaultproducts (commercial e.g. TuneIn and non-Commercial e.g. RadioPlayer). In this instance the BBC has used the licence fee to crowd out these other services for no discernible benefit to licence fee payers, and to the detriment of commercial operators.
default&#xa0;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRadi
defaulto 1's use of video content online has not been clearly articulated to licence fee payers and Radio 1's service licence does not cover the creation of video content that has no direct connection or benefit back to Radio 1 and UK licence fee payers (e.g. Wre
defaultcking ball spoof videos). This is yet another example of Radio1 building a populist service which is already available at no cost to licence fee payers. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA new safeguard of peer review should be instigated to scrutinise plans for new technology projects a
defaultnd launch of such projects. Industry experts should be recruited as an expert panel to reviews plans and report to BBC management about the potential pitfalls and impact. The BBCs response should then be published. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe same peer review panels should cont
defaultinue to regularly review the market impact of BBC products and these reviews should be made public. 
default&#xa0;defaultTransparency, scrutiny and accountability default&#xa0;defaultCommittee Questions 
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?
defaulto
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn a 
defaultconstantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the last ten years the media landscape has changed dram
defaultatically. Technology and new products have transformed consumer choice. The pace of change means that it is not sensible for the BBC to be set up with a ten-year charter that may prevent it from responding to change or lock in behaviour that hampers the pr
defaultoper functioning of the market. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTherefore, a five-year review point for BBC services should be introduced. We understand that the BBC needs stability to plan so would suggest that the review does not impact on funding or the Charter but instead examines 
defaultif each service is delivering on its remit. Each service should be peer reviewed by panels including figures from the private sector and management held accountable for the delivery of a service’
defaults remit. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn order to ensure that the BBC is spending the li
defaultcence fee prudently and effectively the BBC should be more transparent. To increase accountability the BBC should have its accounts audited by the independent NAO each year.  
default&#xa0;
defaultIncreasing transparency coupled with project evaluations and peer review will h
defaultelp avoid wasting money and drive efficiency in the BBC.  
default&#xa0;
defaultConclusion default&#xa0;defaultGlobal supports a successful and efficient BBC delivering distinctive and original content of public value. The BBC governance and public duties need reform if the BBC is going to del
defaultiver more public service content and value for money for licence fee payers. BBC services must have detailed remits for which managers are 
defaultaccountable to limit duplication of content offered by commercial providers and encroachment into commercial territor
defaulty.  
